{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625925"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:30:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17048"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17048"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.29,0.21,0.04,0.38]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76991"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9738"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62497"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5145"},{"type":"tags","id":"5253"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23060"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76991"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVedolizumab is a biological agent used to treat inflammatory bowel disease, including ulcerative colitis and Crohn disease. It is typically prescribed when conventional therapies or other biological agents have not achieved remission.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of vedolizumab?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks complement activation","Blocks \u03b14\u03b27 integrin on lymphocytes","Blocks tumour necrosis factor alpha","Inhibits Janus kinase enzymes","Inhibits interleukin-12 and interleukin-23"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVedolizumab works by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking \u03b14\u03b27 integrin on lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E. This prevents lymphocytes from binding to mucosal addressin cell adhesion molecule-1 (MAdCAM-1) on intestinal vessels, thereby reducing lymphocyte trafficking specifically to the gut and decreasing intestinal inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks complement activation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a mechanism used by current inflammatory bowel disease treatments\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks tumour necrosis factor alpha\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of adalimumab and infliximab, which are first-line biological agents\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits Janus kinase enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of tofacitinib, used primarily in ulcerative colitis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits interleukin-12 and interleukin-23\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the mechanism of ustekinumab, used in moderate to severe Crohn disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gut-selective mechanism of vedolizumab results in fewer systemic side effects compared to other biological agents. It is particularly useful in patients who have failed or lost response to anti-tumour necrosis factor therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Vedolizumab is a monoclonal antibody that selectively blocks \u03b14\u03b27 integrin on lymphocytes.","By blocking gut-specific lymphocyte trafficking, vedolizumab reduces inflammation in inflammatory bowel disease.","Vedolizumab\u0027s gut selectivity results in fewer systemic side effects compared to other biological agents.","Vedolizumab is effective in both ulcerative colitis and Crohn disease when other treatments have failed."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62497"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17048"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62497"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:00:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:02:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9738"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76991"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identif